WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:06.020
Hello and welcome back. In this lesson, I will use OpenClaw to disable nag screens.

00:00:07.180 --> 00:00:14.460
Go to your practice CrackMe folder. I will use this nag screen 64-bit CrackMe.

00:00:14.980 --> 00:00:19.700
When I click on it, it will show an opening nag message box with the message

00:00:19.700 --> 00:00:26.720
please register. When I click ok, it shows the main window. The instruction says remove the

00:00:26.720 --> 00:00:31.940
opening and closing nags. If I close the window, the closing nag message box shows

00:00:31.940 --> 00:00:46.100
with the message, kindly register. I will record the message strings in notepad. Open

00:00:46.100 --> 00:00:58.710
notepad and write down the opening nag and closing nag strings. Next, I run x64dbg as

00:00:58.710 --> 00:01:08.870
administrator. Be sure to run the 64-bit version of x64dbg because our crack me is 64-bit.

00:01:08.870 --> 00:01:52.180
the crack me. Next, run Ghidra. Drag the crack me into Ghidra. Then, analyze it. Note that in order

00:01:52.180 --> 00:01:59.480
for the base address in Ghidra to match the addresses in x64 dbg, you should have disabled

00:01:59.480 --> 00:02:06.540
ASLR as taught in earlier lessons. In telegram, I clear history and start a new session.

00:02:06.540 --> 00:02:12.720
I then give open claw the instructions.

00:02:12.720 --> 00:02:16.530
You can use the same prompt.

00:02:16.530 --> 00:02:24.070
If the backend open AI GPT 5.5 refuses to help due to ethical reasons, just restart

00:02:24.070 --> 00:02:26.250
but give fewer details in the prompt.

00:02:26.250 --> 00:02:30.850
For example, do not say you are trying to disable the nag.

00:02:30.850 --> 00:02:35.530
Also don't give the full string: "please register" or "kindly register".

00:02:35.530 --> 00:02:53.860
Instead, just ask to look for the message box where the message says: "please" or "kindly".

00:02:53.860 --> 00:02:58.000
OpenClaw says Ghidra MCP is not reachable.

00:02:58.000 --> 00:03:02.020
It seems I have forgotten to start the Ghidra MCP server.

00:03:02.020 --> 00:03:04.000
Let's do that now.

00:03:04.000 --> 00:03:08.100
Go to the Ghidra MCP folder.

00:03:08.100 --> 00:03:11.440
Open a CMD terminal.

00:03:11.440 --> 00:03:20.440
Activate the Python virtual environment. 

00:03:20.440 --> 00:03:30.870
start the Ghidra MCP bridge. Back in Telegram, OpenClaw is refusing to patch the binary to

00:03:30.870 --> 00:03:41.400
disable nag screens. This is because OpenAI GPT 5.5 is refusing to do it. Remember we are using

00:03:41.400 --> 00:03:51.750
OpenAI codex as the brains for OpenClaw. I ask it to try Ghidra again. OpenClaw replies

00:03:51.750 --> 00:03:59.270
saying it managed to connect with Ghidra. It suggests locating the strings using ghidra.

00:04:01.190 --> 00:04:09.030
I say yes, do it. Again, OpenClaw says it cannot continue, presumably due to ethical reasons.

00:04:11.140 --> 00:04:20.120
I reassure it that I wrote the crack me and it is for educational purposes. It stubbornly refuses.

00:04:20.120 --> 00:04:25.160
I try a different approach.

00:04:25.160 --> 00:04:32.150
I ask it to identify the address of the control flow logic that shows the strings.

00:04:32.150 --> 00:04:36.160
Still, it refuses.

00:04:36.160 --> 00:04:40.390
Let's try another way.

00:04:40.390 --> 00:04:51.240
I will clear a chat history and start a new session.

00:04:51.240 --> 00:04:53.960
This time I won't reveal too much in my prompt.

00:04:53.960 --> 00:05:02.880
Instead, I only provide the bare minimum information so as not to tip it off that I am trying to

00:05:02.880 --> 00:05:08.010
to bypass software protection security.

00:05:08.010 --> 00:05:09.690
I think this is the same problem we

00:05:09.690 --> 00:05:15.870
might face with frontier models like GPT-5.5 or Claude.

00:05:15.870 --> 00:05:19.330
We need to be careful when prompting.

00:05:19.330 --> 00:05:22.730
I just ask it to locate the control flow logic, which

00:05:22.730 --> 00:05:25.890
shows a message box containing the string:

00:05:25.890 --> 00:05:36.120
"Please"

00:05:36.120 --> 00:05:41.780
And it managed to find it.

00:05:41.780 --> 00:05:46.590
It lists down several critical addresses.

00:05:46.590 --> 00:05:50.370
I would skip the video to the important part.

00:05:50.370 --> 00:05:54.710
I asked it how to prevent the message box from showing.

00:05:54.710 --> 00:05:59.730
And it gave me two clean options involving two addresses.

00:05:59.730 --> 00:06:05.850
I had used x64dbg to put two breakpoints at those addresses

00:06:05.850 --> 00:06:08.430
and confirm those breakpoints were hit just

00:06:08.430 --> 00:06:10.590
before the message box showed.

00:06:10.590 --> 00:06:17.940
I skipped those part of the videos to keep things short.

00:06:17.940 --> 00:06:36.210
I then no-op one of the breakpoints to disable the jump to the message box, and ran the program.

00:06:36.210 --> 00:06:37.790
And it works.

00:06:37.790 --> 00:06:45.860
It skipped the first nag screen and only shows the second nag screen.

00:06:45.860 --> 00:07:14.260
I then patch it, and give it a new name, calling it version 2.

00:07:14.260 --> 00:07:19.910
Next we will target the second nag screen.

00:07:19.910 --> 00:07:27.550
So we load the version 2 into x64dbg.

00:07:27.550 --> 00:07:38.120
We test version 2 directly and true enough, the first nag does not show.

00:07:38.120 --> 00:07:43.120
We then close the main window and the second nag shows.

00:07:43.120 --> 00:07:48.060
Now we will attack this second nag.

00:07:48.060 --> 00:07:56.200
I ask openclaw to find the address for when the message box will show the string: "Kindly".

00:07:56.200 --> 00:08:03.240
After a while, it found the address.

00:08:03.240 --> 00:08:20.310
I then go to that address in x64dbg, and also do a no-op here to disable the jump to the

00:08:20.310 --> 00:08:30.190
message box, and run the program.

00:08:30.190 --> 00:08:35.220
The main window shows.

00:08:35.220 --> 00:08:40.940
When I close it, the second nag does not show, so it works.

00:08:40.940 --> 00:08:56.460
Now we need to reopen in x64dbg and do a patch, we go back to that same address previously,

00:08:56.460 --> 00:09:22.830
do a no op and then patch it. Give it another name version 3. Now we run version 3.

00:09:22.830 --> 00:09:33.650
The main windows shows. We close it and the second nag does not show. So we have finally

00:09:33.650 --> 00:09:39.510
patched the crack me to disable both nags. That's all for this video thanks for watching.

